  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_0' aria-label=\" Amlesh Kumar versus The State of Bihar pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('0','2025','2025_7_394_406','2025INSC810'); ><font size='4'> <strong>AMLESH KUMAR<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>THE STATE OF BIHAR </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 7 S.C.R. 394</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 810</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010002802025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : SANJAY KAROL<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, PRASANNA BHALACHANDRA VARALE</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether in the attending facts and circumstances, the High Court could have accepted a submission of the Sub-Divisional Police Officer, to conduct narco-analysis test of all the accused persons (including the appellant) and other witnesses, during the investigation; whether form the sole basis of conviction in the absence of other evidence on record; whether an accused can voluntarily seek a narco-analysis test, as a matter of an indefeasible right. Headnotes&dagger; Constitution of India &ndash; Art.20(3) and Art.21 &ndash; Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 &ndash;<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 09-06-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CRIMINAL APPEAL No. 2901/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('0','2025','2025_7_394_406','2025INSC810','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'>